1/ Quote pairs are a new value accrual model for tokens https://t.co/2WINLhVXiZ

2/ Quote pairs are a model originally pioneered by @virtuals_io, the model is simple: 

When you originate new coins you set the quote currency as your own token.

You token gate your markets and capture the net value of all of the coins originated.

$ZORA uses this model today https://t.co/Xzm6BmHEGH

3/ Quote pairing does not need to have any negative UX impact. 

Apps can use routing to allow users to still trade using whatever they have in their wallet. 

E.g. even though this coin is paired in $zora, users can buy using ETH, USDC or any other token. https://t.co/spaVjUcp91

4/ Quote pairing works in addition to a transaction fee model. 

This means that apps and labs teams can still generate revenue alongside this token model: this is a big deal.

Transaction fees can be used to operate the team, drive rewards back to the ecosystem and buybacks. https://t.co/Js6haqqohc

5/ In the context of @zora—where we are tokenizing all content—it's likely that we can push this quote model much further to create new connections between content, memes and creators.

Web2 has a social graph weighted by following
$ZORA has a coin graph weighted by markets https://t.co/jNROI7gnkv

6/ Zooming way out, crypto is unbundling money:

- Store of value
- Medium of exchange
- Unit of account

A common assumption is L1 tokens are the center of their ecosystems. With gas abstraction and quote pairing, perhaps that dynamic shifts with the rise of token launchers.

7/ We launched quote pairing with $ZORA just under two weeks ago.

It's fully integrated into our app and teams like 0x are already routing through $zora natively now

https://t.co/xbyAmUPDK5

Assume crypto is all “just speculation” and it’s the superpower of the technology. 

The question is then how to utilize and channel that towards outcomes that further society. 

That’s the frontier of tokenization: unlocking new markets that improve coordination across society.

Speculation is a superpower: its imagination with action. 

Speculation gets a bad wrap in part because until crypto the only real outlet for most people are gambling and the stock market. 

Productive outlets like venture capital was walled off for accredited investors.

Speculation is good.

It’s a raw market force—neutral by default, powerful when channeled.
Supply and demand of speculative assets

I’d posit there’s a relatively fixed pool of speculative demand.

Historically, the supply of speculative assets has been scarce, gated, and institutionally controlled. The supply available to retail has mostly been gambling and stocks.

Crypto exponentially increases that supply https://t.co/Xgk4WY2xfA

The tokenization race: 

As more and more at scale platforms (that already have demand) launch their own chains, the competitive frontier is issuance. 

Win the supply to lock in the demand (and liquidity etc)

Posit: onchain native is more valuable and important to win than things like stocks. 

There will be many competing stock coins for the same stock. 

But being the point of origin for a cryptonative thing means it’s harder for a competing token to exist for the exact same thing. https://t.co/877L3Jhch7
Example: there could be many competing stock coins for a company, but probably only one memecoin. https://t.co/ur1m7zkxE7
